<section class="cg-page">
  <div class="cg-wrap">

    <div class="cg-hero">
      <p class="cg-hero__eyebrow">From the atelier</p>
      <h1 class="cg-hero__title">Caring for your piece</h1>
      <p class="cg-hero__lead">Your Laura Milman piece is made to last several lifetimes. A small amount of considered care — nothing precious, just attentive — keeps a stone bright and a setting sound.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-section">
      <h2 class="cg-section__title">Daily wear</h2>
      <div class="cg-section__body">
        <ul>
          <li>Take your piece off before exercise, swimming, gardening, or applying lotion or perfume.</li>
          <li>Put jewellery on last when getting ready, and take it off first when you return home.</li>
          <li>Store pieces separately — a soft pouch, a lined compartment, or the fitted box your piece arrived in. Diamonds will scratch every other gemstone, including each other.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-section">
      <h2 class="cg-section__title">Cleaning at home</h2>
      <div class="cg-section__body">
        <p>A simple soak between professional visits keeps the stone catching the light.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Fill a small bowl with warm — not hot — water and a few drops of mild dish soap.</li>
          <li>Soak the piece for fifteen to twenty minutes.</li>
          <li>Brush gently with a soft-bristled toothbrush, paying attention to the underside of the setting where lotion and skin oils collect.</li>
          <li>Rinse under warm running water (close the drain first).</li>
          <li>Pat dry with a lint-free cloth. Allow to air-dry fully before wearing.</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Professional cleaning:</strong> we recommend an annual visit to a trusted jeweller for an ultrasonic clean and a prong inspection. It is a short appointment that catches small issues before they become large ones.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-section">
      <h2 class="cg-section__title">Caring for the metal</h2>
      <div class="cg-section__body">

        <h3 class="cg-section__sub">Gold — 14k and 18k</h3>
        <p>Polish with a soft cloth regularly. Keep harsh chemicals away. Gold develops a natural patina with wear, which many find lovely; a professional polish restores a mirror finish whenever you prefer one.</p>

        <h3 class="cg-section__sub">Platinum</h3>
        <p>Platinum acquires a satiny patina over years of wear — again, often beloved. A professional re-polish returns the mirror finish. Platinum holds prongs more tightly than gold, which makes it a quietly excellent choice for a piece worn every day.</p>

        <h3 class="cg-section__sub">Rose gold</h3>
        <p>Treat as you would yellow or white gold. The copper alloy gives rose gold its warmth — keep it away from chlorine, which can shift the colour over time.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-section">
      <h2 class="cg-section__title">What to avoid</h2>
      <div class="cg-section__body">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Chlorine</strong> — swimming pools, hot tubs. Weakens gold alloys with repeated exposure.</li>
          <li><strong>Bleach and harsh household chemicals.</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Home ultrasonic cleaners</strong> on fragile settings (pavé, tension, channel).</li>
          <li><strong>Sleeping in rings</strong> — can bend prongs out of true.</li>
          <li><strong>Hand sanitiser</strong> applied while wearing rings — the alcohol dries the metal and skin.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-section">
      <h2 class="cg-section__title">When to bring a piece in</h2>
      <div class="cg-section__body">
        <ul>
          <li>A stone that rattles or spins in its setting — a prong likely needs a slight retighten.</li>
          <li>Visibly bent or worn prongs.</li>
          <li>Surface scratches you would like polished out.</li>
          <li>An annual once-over even if nothing seems amiss.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="cg-tip">
      <strong>Worth knowing:</strong> a Laura Milman diamond is a 10 on the Mohs hardness scale — the hardest material on earth. It will not cloud, dull, or lose its fire over decades of wear.
    </div>

    <div class="cg-faq">
      <h2 class="cg-faq__heading">Frequently asked</h2>

      <div class="cg-faq__item">
        <p class="cg-faq__q">Will my diamond grow cloudy with time?</p>
        <p class="cg-faq__a">No. Lab-grown diamonds share the crystal structure and hardness of mined diamonds. They will not cloud, haze, or degrade in any way — ever.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="cg-faq__item">
        <p class="cg-faq__q">Can I wear my ring in the shower?</p>
        <p class="cg-faq__a">We would gently advise against it. Soap residue collects on and beneath the stone and dulls the sparkle, and a wet finger is a more slippery one. A small ring dish by the sink is a worthy investment.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="cg-faq__item">
        <p class="cg-faq__q">How often should I clean a piece at home?</p>
        <p class="cg-faq__a">Every two to four weeks at home with warm water and mild soap, and once a year by a jeweller for an ultrasonic clean and prong inspection.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

